    <segment id="1" parent="26" relname="solutionhood">I, for one, am still puzzled by methodological relativism.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="16" relname="preparation">  The point 
seems to be:</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="4" relname="condition"> If writing a history of an episode in science,</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="17" relname="span"> do not 
presume the outcome in the history.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="17" relname="restatement">  Or, more narrowly, evaluate each 
phase of the episode only on the information available to the 
participants at that phase.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="19" relname="span">

Sounds utterly uncontroversial</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="elaboration"> -- it is not so much anti-Whig as I 
commitment to viewing scientists as not blessed with precognition.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="9" relname="background">

The question is, again, the very one raised by Schmaus</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="25" relname="span"> -- who doesn&apos;t do 
history this way?</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="23" relname="span">

By the way, this is not a rhetorical question.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="22" relname="span">  I am hoping that Schmaus 
has raised the tone of the debate by doing just what Collins has asked in 
the past -- discussing examples. </segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="11" relname="elaboration"> So, who has written bad history of the 
Michelson-Morley debate? </segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="14" relname="solutionhood"> Is it the history in the science textbooks that 
is at issue? </segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="20" relname="span"> That would be interesting,</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="21" relname="span"> as it would indicate why 
scientists might react to Collins&apos; cases as falsified history.</segment>
